  "source": "Theorem:\n. \"Theorem 4.33 (Transfinite Induction)\"\ngiven:\n. X is \\set\n. S is \\set\nwhere:\n. \\well.ordered{X}\n. S \\:subset:/ X\n. forAll: x is \\set\n  where:\n  . x \"in\" X\n  then:\n  . if:\n    . \\initial.segment:in{X}:of{x} \\:subset:/ S\n    then:\n    . x \"in\" S\nthen:\n. S = X\nDocumented:\n. description: \"Suppose $X$ is well ordered and $S \\subseteq X$ is such that for all $x \\in X$, if $s(x) \\subseteq S$ then $x \\in S$. Then $S = X$. This is the analogue for well ordered sets of the principle of mathematical induction.\"\nId: \"fd837670-a02e-4c69-b64c-5dd470fa1696\"",
